<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-1-1412> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Van sparrenwortels werden door vrouwen kegelvormige hoeden gevlochten, zij het dat de bovenkant niet spits was maar afgeplat, en de onderrand soms breed uitliep. Onversierde hoeden werden door zowel mannen als vrouwen gedragen.\r\n\r\nVoor statushoeden werden soms twee verschillende vlechttechnieken gebruikt. Voor de onderzijde was dat een techniek die een mooi oppervlakte reliëf opleverde. De bovenzijde was zo vlak als mogelijk geweven omdat deze vervolgens werd voorzien van beschildering, uitgevoerd door mannen. Daarbij werden de mythologische clanfiguren afgebeeld, in gestileerde vorm, meestal in zwart en rood uitgevoerd, soms aangevuld met blauw-groen. Vaak was de gehele hoed hetzelfde gevlochten en beschilderd. Dergelijke hoeden werden gedragen door clan- en dorpshoofden, bij feestelijke gelegenheden. Soms waren enkele brede gevlochten ringen boven op de hoed aangebracht. Deze verwijzen in ieder geval naar hoge status, maar de vroegere interpretatie dat het aantal ringen het aantal gegeven potlatches weergeven, wordt niet langer meer gevolgd.\r\n\r\nEnkele schilders van gevlochten statushoeden brachten een signatuur aan op de hoed, meestal op de afgeplatte top, en vaak in de vorm van een ster. Aan de hand van het aantal stralen en de kleuren van de ster wist men wie de hoed had beschilderd. Tom Price (Haida) gebruikte een vijfpuntige rode ster; Charles Edenshaw (Haida) een vierpuntige ster, verdeeld in rode en zwarte segmenten op de hoeden die door zijn vrouw Isabelle waren gevlochten.\r\n\r\nDeze gevlochten kegelvormige hoeden waren vooral kenmerkend voor de stammen van de noordelijke Noordwest kust: Tlingits en Haidas. Er is gesuggereerd dat dit type hoed was ontleend aan Chinese zeelieden die op het schip van John Meares werkten dat in 1788 dit kustgebied bezocht. Echter, dergelijke hoeden zijn ook opgegraven in prehistorische nederzettingen, hetgeen hun autochtone ontwikkeling lijkt te bevestigen.\r\n\r\nMeer platte breedgerande hoeden van gevlochten sparrenwortels waren kenmerkend voor de noordelijke buren van de Tlingits en Haidas: de Inuït (Eskimos). De beschildering bestaat weliswaar uit gestileerde figuren van dieren en mythologische wezens, maar wijkt toch duidelijk af van de karakteristieke vormlijn-stijl van de Noordwest kust Indianen.\r\n\r\nEngelse tekst\r\nTlingit hat; 1790-1835\r\nSpruce root, pigments; h. 16 cm., w. 29 cm.\r\nRMV 1-1412; Philip Franz Von Siebold collection, 1837\r\n  \r\nItems of regalia on the Northwest Coast are renowned for their elaborate, powerful designs and excellent construction. Woven in the early nineteenth century, this hat provides a glimpse of Tlingit society, artistry, and gender cooperation. Spruce root hats served several purposes which were reflected in their form; the most common were undecorated, utilitarian hats worn as protection from the elements. While intricate crest art was carved and painted on house posts, boxes and other essential items, the painting of crests on hats was reserved for those hats with the finest weave, to be worn by upper class men and women at ceremonies and other formal events (Glinsman 2006).\r\n\r\nThe process of creating this item of regalia was long and complex. Spruce root was harvested from the ground, heated over a fire, stripped of its husk, split into fine strands, sorted into grades of varying quality, and finally twined over a period of weeks or even months. The woman who wove this hat made several choices in its construction.  Using very finely split spruce root, she made the top and crown in three-strand twining. This technique results not only in a strong structure; it provides a smooth surface on which to paint very fine imagery as we see here. She used a single row of braided twining to transition between the top and crown, and the crown and the brim. On the brim, she used skip stitches in rows to create a design sweeping down from the left to the right. To flare the hat, she not only added warps but also widened the existing warps, thickening them with additional strands of spruce root. In this way, the pattern of the brim was made uniform while steadily expanding. She was a careful weaver, aligning her design transitions in one place. It is even possible that she instructed the painter to paint the creature with the transitions at the back, where they appear just to the right of the center back.\r\n\r\nAccomplished male artists painted hats with crest designs indicating the lineage and rank of a specific person or clan. Thus, men were the transformers of hats – from utility to eminence. The painter of this hat was virtuosic in his use of Tlingit visual vocabulary. He seamlessly incorporated ovoids, u-forms and salmon-trout-heads in the crown design, which depicts a creature with ears above the double-eye sockets and fins on the back of the hat. The one-step structure of the face has fully-realized primary, secondary and tertiary formline features in black, red and light blue-green. The four-pointed star on top of the hat is red on a blue-green ground; the brim is also blue-green.\r\n\r\nWhile many hats of this era embody the dialogue of trade and innovation present among Northwest Coast peoples at the dawn of the nineteenth century, the weaving and painting materials, techniques and personal choices evident in this hat all reflect its Tlingit origins. In painted designs of this period, influence from the Tlingits’ northern neighbors is often evident in the form of more angular formline and additional design elements such as rows of circles. That is clearly not the case here. As for the weaving, this particular combination of techniques is not found in earlier hats, which used diverse methods of ornament and construction. This hat then represents a point of consolidation of a Tlingit weaving archetype.\r\n\r\nWhat purpose might this particular hat have served? The headband, woven into the fabric of the hat on the underside, is wide and substantial. A remnant of a leather chin strap is still securely fastened to one side of the headband. Altogether it shows some wear, but none of the sort that a traveling or everyday hat would have. It was conceived and woven as a hat for a person of high status, worn only occasionally at celebratory feasts and other affairs where the display of the crest was an essential centerpiece in highlighting the prestige of the hat’s owner.\r\n\r\nDawn Glinsman\r\nBurke Museum of Natural History and Culture, Seattle, WA; 2015\r\n\r\n\r\nDawn Glinsman, Northern Northwest Coast Spruce Root hats. Ph.D.-thesis; University of Washington; Seattle, 2006." .
